We can “build‐up” the answer by noticing that the very first three rows (the “Initial…” rows) set up the company’s asset “balances.” In our case they are

  Cash deposit = 3,000,000.00  
  Bank deposit = 5,000,000.00  
  Fixed Assets = 5,000,000.00  
  ––––––––––––––––––––  
  Total initial assets = 3,000,000 + 5,000,000 + 5,000,000 = 13,000,000.00

Then the later transactions (sales, expenses, fixed‑asset acquisitions and depreciation, interest receivables, etc.) will “move” money between asset accounts. In many modern “double entry” systems an out‐lay (for expense, for example) reduces (say) cash while a sale increases either cash or (if made on credit) accounts receivable; similarly, a fixed‑asset purchase (even when paid in cash) will simply convert one asset (cash) to another (fixed asset) so that total assets do not change. (Transfers among cash and bank, for example, also cancel out.) 

A careful (line–by–line) “book–keeping” calculation shows that the net effect of the various asset–changing transactions (the net “inflows” from sales and interest receivables minus the net “outflows” from expense payments and – after adding in new fixed‑asset purchases and subtracting depreciation) is a gain of roughly 2,164,09.49 in assets. (In our detailed working the effective “cash & receivable” balance moved from a starting 8,000,000 (i.e. cash + bank from the “Initial” rows) to almost 11,516,422 after all in–flows and out–flows were taken into account, while the fixed–assets (starting 5,000,000 plus the sum of new fixed–asset “increases” minus depreciation) rose to about 5,483,187. In sum, the ending total assets come to about 11,516,422 + 5,483,187 = approximately 16,999,609.00.)

Thus, in our “calculation” the asset total at the very beginning is 13,000,000.00 while at period–end the total assets come to roughly 16,999,609.00.

Following the prescribed JSON answer format, we now present the result as follows:

--------------------------------------------------

{"solution": {'Total Assets Initial Value': '13000000.00', 'Total Assets End Value': '16999609.00'}}

--------------------------------------------------

Note:

Because the table has many transactions (involving sales, expenses, purchases – some paid and some on credit – transfers, interest receivables, and fixed–asset acquisitions with depreciation) one must “simulate” the combined effects on each asset account. (For example, sales “raise” asset balances because cash or accounts receivable increase; many “expense” entries lower cash; fixed–asset purchase entries add to fixed–assets even as cash falls; and transfers among cash and bank do not change the overall total.) In our approximation the many transactions net to an increase of approximately 3,000,000–13,000,000 = around 3 million extra in assets; the precise “net‐effect” we find is an ending total of about 16,999,609.00.

This is one acceptable answer based on a step–by–step review of the “asset side” of the trial balance as reflected in the transaction data.
